  3. Set invariant on G' with same set - use wf_e_of_cons: since vars_lt n e_nat (from condition 5)
     and n ≤ n (le_refl), wf_e G' el er with to_nat er = e_nat implies wf_e G el er by wf_e_of_cons.
     Then the old set invariant applies.
  4. Counter freshness: new entry has n < n+1. Old entries: < n < n+1.
  5. Set vars bound: vars_lt (n+1) from vars_lt n by vars_lt_mono with n ≤ n+1.
  6. Uniqueness: new entry has r.1 = n. Old entries have r.1 < n. So no collision.

Case eq0 el cl' ih: wf gives cr = .eq0 er cr' with wf_e G el er and wf G cl' cr'.
  dedup_ (.eq0 er cr') n set = if to_nat er ∈ set then dedup_ cr' n set else .eq0 (to_var er) (dedup_ cr' n (to_nat er :: set)).

  Need Circuit.eq0 el cl' ≈ (if to_nat er ∈ set then dedup_ cr' n set else ...).

  Unfold ≈ as eval equality. eval (.eq0 el cl') = if el.eval = 0 then eval cl' else .n.

  Split on whether to_nat er ∈ set:

  Subcase to_nat er ∈ set:
    By set invariant: el.eval = 0 (since wf_e G el er and to_nat er = to_nat er).
    So eval (.eq0 el cl') = eval cl'.
    Need eval cl' = eval (dedup_ cr' n set).
    Apply ih with same G, n, set and all conditions unchanged.

  Subcase to_nat er ∉ set:
    eval (dedup_) = if (to_var er).eval = 0 then eval (dedup_ cr' n (to_nat er :: set)) else .n.
    By to_var_sem_pre: el.eval = (to_var er).eval (i.e., el ≈ to_var er).
    So the conditions match: if el.eval = 0 then ... else .n on both sides.
    For the then-branch: need eval cl' = eval (dedup_ cr' n (to_nat er :: set)).

    But this must hold unconditionally (not just when el.eval = 0)!
    Actually no - we need the full equality if el.eval = 0 then eval cl' else .n = if el.eval = 0 then eval (dedup_ ...) else .n.
    This follows from: eval cl' = eval (dedup_ cr' n (to_nat er :: set)).

    Apply ih with G, n, set' = to_nat er :: set.
    For the set invariant on set': for the new entry to_nat er, we need:
      ∀ el' er', wf_e G el' er' → to_nat er' = to_nat er → el'.eval = 0.
    We don't know el.eval = 0 unconditionally, but we need the proof to work regardless.

    ACTUALLY: we can prove it differently. We need:
      if el.eval = 0 then eval cl' else .n = if (to_var er).eval = 0 then eval (dedup_ cr' n (to_nat er :: set)) else .n

    Since el.eval = (to_var er).eval, this simplifies to:
      if el.eval = 0 then eval cl' else .n = if el.eval = 0 then eval (dedup_ ...) else .n

    Case el.eval = 0: need eval cl' = eval (dedup_ cr' n (to_nat er :: set)).
      Apply ih. The set invariant for the new entry holds because el.eval = 0 and by to_var_determined_by_to_nat, for any el' er' with wf_e G el' er' and to_nat er' = to_nat er, we have to_var er' = to_var er, so el'.eval = (to_var er').eval = (to_var er).eval = el.eval = 0.

    Case el.eval ≠ 0: both sides are .n. Done.

    Use if_congr or split_ifs to handle this.

Case share el kl ih: Similar to lam. wf gives cr = .share er kr with wf_e G el er and ∀ xl xr, wf ({l:=xl, r:=xr}::G) (kl xl) (kr xr).
  dedup_ (.share er kr) n set = .share (to_var er) (fun x => dedup_ (kr (n, x)) (n+1) set).
  eval (.share el kl) = eval (kl el.eval).
  eval (.share (to_var er) ...) = eval (dedup_ (kr (n, (to_var er).eval)) (n+1) set).
  Since el.eval = (to_var er).eval (by to_var_sem_pre), let v = el.eval.
  Need eval (kl v) = eval (dedup_ (kr (n, v)) (n+1) set).
  Apply ih with G' = {l:=v, r:=(n,v)}::G, n+1, set. Same condition verification as lam case.

